              "fullExplanation": null,
              "modelAnswer": "---\n## 10. Reflection and Next Steps\n\n### What We Covered Today\n\nThis lab built a solid statistical foundation for reasoning about **samples and uncertainty**:\n\n- **Population vs sample** established the fundamental distinction between the complete\n  set of interest and the subset we observe, including the difference between finite and\n  infinite populations.\n- **Sampling methods** showed why *how* we sample matters — probability-based methods\n  allow us to quantify error, while convenience sampling introduces systematic bias.\n- **Sample statistics** ($\\bar{X}$, $S^2$) are themselves random variables with their own\n  distributions — the sampling distributions.\n- **The Central Limit Theorem** demonstrated that the distribution of $\\bar{X}$ converges\n  to a Normal distribution regardless of the population shape, provided $n$ is large enough.\n  This is the single most important theorem underpinning statistical inference.\n- **Confidence intervals** translated point estimates into honest ranges that communicate\n  uncertainty, and the **margin of error** quantified the precision of those estimates.\n- **The Chi-square distribution** arose from the sampling distribution of the sample\n  variance and enables inference about population variability.\n- **Student's $t$-distribution** addressed the realistic scenario where $\\sigma$ is unknown,\n  producing appropriately wider intervals that account for the additional estimation\n  uncertainty.\n\n### Connection to AI\n\nThese ideas are fundamental in machine learning practice:\n- **Cross-validation** and **bootstrap** methods are sampling strategies for model evaluation.\n- **Confidence intervals on accuracy** are required when reporting model performance.\n- **A/B testing** (comparing two models) relies on the CLT and CI theory.\n- **Bayesian deep learning** uses posterior distributions that connect to the $t$-distribution.\n- **Batch size** in stochastic gradient descent affects the variance of gradient estimates,\n  directly analogous to the $\\sigma^2/n$ relationship we studied today.\n\n### Looking Ahead\n\nIn the coming weeks we will build on these foundations to study:\n- **Hypothesis Testing** — using sampling distributions to make formal decisions about\n  population parameters.\n- **Information Theory** — entropy, KL divergence, and cross-entropy as mathematical\n  foundations of loss functions.\n\n### Reflection Questions (not assessed)\n\n1. A colleague says \"the 95 % CI means there is a 95 % probability that $\\mu$ is inside the\n   interval.\" Why is this interpretation incorrect, and what is the correct one?\n2. If you needed to evaluate a rare-event classifier (e.g. detecting fraud at a 0.1 % rate),\n   how would the required test-set size compare to a balanced classifier?\n3. Why does the $t$-distribution have heavier tails than the Normal? What real-world\n   consequence does this have for small-sample inference?\n4. In what sense is the Central Limit Theorem \"the reason statistics works\"?\n\n---\n\n**End of Week 7 Lab — Well done!** 🎉\n\n*If you found any errors or have suggestions, please raise them in the next seminar session.*",
