              "modelAnswer": "---\n## 10. Reflection and Next Steps\n\n### What We Covered Today\n\nThis lab traced the complete mathematical pathway from elementary calculus to\n**backpropagation**, the algorithm that trains modern neural networks:\n\n- **Derivatives** as instantaneous rates of change, computed via the difference quotient\n  and interpreted as tangent slopes.\n- **Partial derivatives** for multivariable functions — differentiating one variable at a\n  time while treating others as constants.\n- **The gradient** as the vector of all partial derivatives, pointing in the direction of\n  steepest ascent with magnitude equal to the steepness.\n- **Gradient descent** as the iterative procedure for minimising loss functions by following\n  the negative gradient, controlled by the learning rate.\n- **The chain rule** for differentiating composed functions: sequential compositions multiply,\n  and parallel paths add.\n- **Computation graphs** as the visual and computational framework for organising complex\n  function compositions.\n- **Forward and backward passes** through computation graphs: forward to compute outputs,\n  backward to compute gradients.\n- **Backpropagation** as the systematic, efficient application of the chain rule in reverse\n  through a computation graph — the algorithm that makes training deep neural networks\n  computationally feasible.\n\n### The Big Picture\n\nEvery deep learning framework — PyTorch, TensorFlow, JAX — is fundamentally a sophisticated\nimplementation of what you did by hand today. When you call `loss.backward()` in PyTorch,\nit is performing exactly the backward pass you implemented: traversing the computation\ngraph in reverse, applying the chain rule at each node, and accumulating gradients. The\nmathematics is identical; the frameworks simply automate it at scale.\n\n### Looking Ahead\n\n- **Optimisation algorithms** (SGD with momentum, Adam, RMSProp) build on the gradient\n  descent foundation we established today.\n- **Automatic differentiation** libraries automate the manual backpropagation process.\n- **Information theory** (next topic) will connect the loss functions we minimise to\n  fundamental measures of information and uncertainty.\n\n### Reflection Questions (not assessed)\n\n1. Why does gradient descent follow the *negative* gradient instead of the gradient itself?\n2. If a function has a saddle point, what does the gradient look like there? Why might\n   gradient descent get stuck?\n3. Explain in your own words why the chain rule is \"all you need\" to train a neural network\n   with millions of parameters.\n4. What would happen if we set the learning rate $\\eta$ to exactly zero?\n\n---\n\n**End of Week 9 Lab — Well done!** 🎉\n\n*If you found any errors or have suggestions, please raise them in the next seminar session.*",
